<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Laing gets NatWest Tower contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
John Laing, the UK construction group, has won the main contract to
refurbish London's NatWest Tower, which was severely damaged in a terrorist
bomb attack in April 1993, Andrew Taylor writes.
The contract for work on Britain's second-tallest building is thought to be
worth about Pounds 80m.
The 42-storey property, previously housed the headquarters of National
Westminster's high street banking operations.
Mr David Edmonds, NatWest's property and central services general manager,
said yesterday that a decision on how the building was to be reoccupied
would not be taken until closer to the completion of the refurbishment in
December 1996.
The bank intends to reclad the exterior of the building in its original
style. It will, however, redesign the interior.
Schmidlin UK has been awarded the cladding sub-contract. Crown House
Engineering has been awarded mechanical and electrical and public health
sub-contracts. The architects are GMW Partnership, assisted by Richard
Seifert and Partners, the original architects of the tower.
