<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Post Office support for sell-off rapped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party yesterday attacked Post Office chiefs who announced that
they backed government plans to sell 51 per cent of the Royal Mail and
Parcelforce to the private sector.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said that yesterday's
response from the Post Office to the government's green paper had 'more to
do with the best interests of the board members than it has to do with the
best interests of a public service Post Office'.
He added: 'As in every other privatisation, I am sure the directors of the
Post Office would do very well out of a sell-off. The same can't be said for
the rest of the workforce or for the consumers.'
Mr Hugh Dykes, one of the Tory MPs opposed to Post Office privatisation,
also criticised the management's public stand. He said: 'The suspicion is
bound to linger in the public mind that senior executives are not only in
favour of full privatisation for what they perceive as genuine operational
objectives, but also as an opportunity to reward themselves like some water
company chiefs.'
Mr Michael Heron, Post Office chairman, urged ministers to decide on the
future of postal services as soon as possible after the consultation period
on the green paper ended on September 30 and warned that the business could
'go into decline' if it did not secure commercial freedom.
Mr Bill Cockburn, Post Office chief executive, denied that post offices were
at risk of closure with the proposed move to 51 per cent private ownership.
He accused opponents of 'scaremongering'. Under the proposed option, he
said, post would continue to be delivered to every address from Monday to
Saturday in a uniform tariff structure. Postal counters would remain in the
public sector but be free to provide a wider range of services.
The Post Office also sought to deny suggestions that privatisation would
lead to higher prices.
It said: 'When market forces are increasing and customers have more choice
than ever before, it is in Royal Mail's commercial interests to keep a tight
control on prices.'
The UCW communications union accused the Post Office of 'irresponsibly
ignoring the overwhelming views of their workforce, many major mail users
and above all the British public'.
Mr Derek Hodgson, UCW deputy general secretary, said: 'Commercial freedom
for an integrated Post Office in the public sector is practical, popular and
achievable. Other European postal administrations operate in this way.'
The Department of Trade and Industry has commissioned audio-tape and braille
versions of the green paper.
Braille and audio-tape versions of green paper. Claire Campbell, Talking
Newspaper Enterprises, National Recording Centre, Heathfield, East Sussex,
TN21 8DB. Tel: 0435 866102. Fax: 0435 865422. Braille summary free. Audio
cassette version Pounds 6.50.
</TEXT>
