<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / C&amp;G plays democratic numbers game: The pitfalls facing the
building society's revised deal with Lloyds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is one of the oddities of democracy in building societies that the board
of Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society should be encouraging even those
who oppose its plan to join the Lloyds Bank group to express their views by
voting.
The C&amp;G board is right to do so - in the interests of its plans to accept
the Pounds 1.8bn cash offer from Lloyds as well as the proper exercise of
rights in a mutually owned organisation.
Its revised scheme for sharing out the cash which was published yesterday is
more likely to hit the hurdle of stringent requirements on the turnout among
investing members approving the deal than it is to fall at the necessary
majorities of those voting.
In terms of borrowing members, a simple majority of those voting is all that
is required. If only three of the 370,000 or so borrowers voted, and two
were in favour, that would be enough.
But the position of investing members causes more problems, particularly
since the High Court ruled in June that the original proposals were
unlawful.
The investors' resolution must be approved by at least 75 per cent of those
who vote. It must also be approved by at least half of the number of
investors eligible to vote, or investors holding 90 per cent of the total
balances of those eligible to vote.
So if opposition to the plan appears almost non-existent many investors who
favour the Lloyds bid could conclude that the deal will go through without
their bothering to vote.
This would carry the risk that the resolution would fall not because the
majority was too low among those voting, but because too few supporters cast
their votes.
C&amp;G's original scheme addressed this by giving a cash handout to every
member which would have acted as an incentive to vote. Investors could have
received up to Pounds 10,000 each and borrowers would have received Pounds
500 cash.
But the ruling by Sir Donald Nicholls, the vice-chancellor, that cash could
be paid neither to investors of less than two years' standing at the
qualifying date nor to any borrowers has made members' reaction to the
current scheme more doubtful than if the first plan had not been put
forward.
First, borrowers who thought they were going to get a cash sum will now have
to be content with hints about the good life they will enjoy as part of
Lloyds Bank. But the absence of a turnout requirement makes this less
significant than it would otherwise be.
Second, investors who became members of the society after the end of 1992
will have had the prospect of cash payments snatched from them, but will
still be entitled to vote.
Even if they blame the law rather than the society, they may think it is
worth trying to stymie the deal on the basis that by the time another one
comes along they are likely to have been members long enough to qualify for
cash.
But this group of disappointed C&amp;G members will not be anything like as big
as the 27 per cent it would have been had the original cut-off point of the
end of 1991 been retained. It may amount to less than 10 per cent of the
potential electorate. If that is so, they would not be able to stop the deal
on their own.
There is, however, a third aspect which may cause C&amp;G to pause for thought.
The months of discussion about the offer have been a consciousness-raising
experience for C&amp;G members. There are those who believe that the offer
undervalues the society and who would like to see a competing bid, or who
want more discussion of floating the society as an alternative strategy.
Mr Paul Rivlin and Mr Peter Nicholson, who organise a group of C&amp;G members
wanting to consider an alternative to the Lloyds offer, are seeking the
support of 100 members to call a special general meeting. Mr Nicholson said
yesterday that at such a meeting they would demand further information from
C&amp;G - including the number of members who were not eligible for cash but
could vote, and the length of the 'shut-out' period during which C&amp;G has
agreed not to talk to other potential bidders.
Yesterday's announcement may give the group enough impetus to force a
general meeting by October.
But the history of building society members' quiescent involvement in the
organisations they own suggests that even this would be a hiccup in the
process rather than a hammer blow to the deal.
</TEXT>
<XX>
