<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Watchdog clears travel operators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Office of Fair Trading yesterday cleared the package travel industry of
anti-competitive behaviour and said no formal action was needed.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, said consumers had a
wide choice of competitively priced holidays in spite of ownership links
between big tour operators and travel agents. He said the links did not
prevent smaller companies from selling their holidays.
Sir Bryan added: 'Vertical integration may make it more difficult for
newcomers to enter the market, but there is no evidence at the moment that
any of the leading operators with agency links have been able to insulate
themselves from competition.'
He was concerned that customers might not be aware of links between travel
agents and operators, and urged companies to make customers aware of such
links.
The findings were welcomed by Thomson and Airtours, the two largest
operators. Thomson owns Lunn Poly, the largest travel retail chain. Airtours
owns Going Places, the second largest. Both said their branches already
carried signs explaining their links with the operators which owned them.
The Association of Independent Tour Operators attacked the findings. Ms Sue
Ockwell, chief executive, said: 'It's bad news for independent tour
operators and travel agents and that, in turn, means it's bad for the
public.
'When you go into a travel agent you expect a choice, you expect independent
travel advice and you don't get that from the big companies. The OFT have
just sat back and said they find that acceptable.'
Sir Bryan said, however, that the watchdog had examined the practices about
which small companies had complained. These included the payment of
discriminatory rates of commission to different travel agents, the refusal
by some agents to carry the brochures of certain tour operators, and agents
promoting their parent companies' holidays. Sir Bryan said he had paid
particular attention to Thomson and Lunn Poly.
He said the central issue was 'whether any such practices significantly
damaged the ability to compete fairly of independent travel agencies or
operators who do not hold shares in travel agencies.' He added: 'Bearing in
mind the relatively large number of tour operators and travel agents and the
evidence of vigorous competition, I do not consider the allegations of
anti-competitive behaviour to be substantiated.'
</TEXT>
