<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / City regulator imposes life ban on former investment
advisers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Regulators yesterday barred two former investment advisers from the industry
for life, bringing to four the individuals banned under section 59 of the
Financial Services Act.
The Securities and Investments Board earlier this year made convicted
fraudster Mr Roger Levitt the first target of its barring powers.
The two named yesterday are Mr Peter Glennie - the target of a High Court
injunction last year preventing him from collecting insurance premiums for
policies that did not appear to exist - and Mr John Charles Miles, who was
convicted in 1989 of theft and sentenced to five years in prison.
Mr Miles, who also operated as John Carrington Miller and Jonathan Charles
Miles, later became an independent financial adviser associated with Knight
Williams, a chain of independent financial advisers, providing false
references to facilitate his employment.
Knight Williams filed a writ last year against Mr Miles seeking damages for
fraudulent misrepresentation of his employment history and providing
fraudulent references.
While employed by Knight Williams, the writ alleged, Mr Miles induced his
clients to invest funds in a company which he controlled. That investment
business was not authorised under the Financial Services Act and violated
the terms of his employment by Knight Williams.
In the case of Mr Glennie, who traded as John Allen and Co, SIB
investigators had been looking into the cases of an estimated 200 clients
for whom insurance premiums had been collected but not passed on to the
relevant insurance company.
The second of the four to be barred came earlier this year when SIB also
made a permanent disqualification order against Mr Christopher Fallon, a
financial adviser jailed for nine months for conducting unauthorised
investment business after having been the subject of a High Court injunction
barring him from doing so.
After the injunction was served on Mr Fallon he took Pounds 24,000 from two
individuals. This was not recovered and because the investment business was
unauthorised, they could not seek compensation under the Investors
Compensation Scheme.
</TEXT>
