<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Cross-border deals show strong rise: US reclaims role as
magnet for foreign capital, survey reveals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mergers and acquisitions of companies across international borders reached
Dollars 77bn (Pounds 50bn) in the first half of 1994, according to a report
published yesterday. That represents a 10 per cent increase on the sums
spent on deals in the second half of last year but is still below the
Dollars 90bn of deals made in the first half of 1993.
One of the most striking trends revealed in the report by KPMG Peat Marwick,
the accountancy and consultancy firm, is that the US has returned to 'its
traditional role as a magnet for foreign capital' helped by the weakness of
the dollar and the resurgence of economic growth.
In the first six months of the year, foreign companies spent Dollars 26bn on
more than 300 acquisitions, joint ventures and minority investments in US
companies.
Foreign spending in the US is 'on track to surpass last year's total by
almost 50 per cent', the survey says.
That marks a reversal of the pattern of the last two years, when US
companies spent more on acquisitions abroad than foreign companies did in
the US. In 1992, US companies spent Dollars 22bn on 824 foreign deals, and
imported Dollars 14bn through 528 transactions. Last year, US companies
spent Dollars 38bn on 942 deals but foreign companies spent only Dollars
33bn on 570 deals.
However, despite the dollar's weakness this year against sterling, the
historically strong level of deals between US and UK companies fell by 30
per cent to around Dollars 16bn in the first six months of 1994, the survey
says.
Last year, UK companies were responsible for four of the six largest foreign
takeovers of US companies. But so far this year, SmithKline Beecham's
acquisition of Diversified Pharmaceutical Services from United Healthcare
has been the only UK deal to figure in the top six foreign takeovers by
value as ranked by KPMG.
It also notes a 70 per cent drop in spending by Japanese companies on
foreign acquisitions, which may reflect political and economic uncertainty.
But the drop in the value of US companies, measured in yen, is likely to
tempt Japanese companies back into deal making, the survey predicts.
The survey also notes that there were sharp drops in spending in acquisition
investment in Russia and China, from a combined total of Dollars 22bn in
both countries in 1993 to only Dollars 5bn in the first half of 1994. It
attributes this to the collapse of the Russian economy and to human rights
tensions in China.
Following last year's successful completion of the North American Free Trade
Agreement, deals across the borders of Nafta countries - the US, Mexico and
Canada - appear to be sharply up in the first half of 1994. Despite
political unrest in Mexico, deals total Dollars 7bn so far this year,
compared to Dollars 11.4bn in the whole of 1993 and Dollars 2.5bn in 1991.
The 1994 figures - and the bidding for Del Monte and Westin Hotels - reflect
the new aggression of Mexican buyers, the survey notes. Already, in the
first six months of 1994, Mexican purchasers have spent as much as they did
in the past three years.
However the survey comments that, in theory, the lowering of trade barriers
through deals such as Nafta 'reduces the need to acquire cross-borders'.
KPMG Quarterly Survey of Cross-border Transactions, KPMG New York, Tel 212
909 5108
</TEXT>
