<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / World Trade News: Hanoi warns over abuse of licences
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEREMY GRANT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HANOI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Vietnam has said it will fine the growing number of foreign companies that
are abusing representative office licences issued by the government.
Representative offices are often an investor's first step into Vietnam but
their licence only allows marketing and liaison. They are not allowed to
receive income in Vietnam.
However, an increasing number of foreign investors are using them for
trading and carrying out business transactions. They say this is because the
rules applying to representative offices are not in keeping with the present
investment climate.
'They were essential in the early years (of foreign investment) when people
came to do feasibility studies,' said one US consultant based in Hanoi. 'But
now people are actually trying to do business.'
Foreign representative offices found violating their charter will be fined
Dollars 50,000 and will be subjected to surprise inspections by the ministry
of trade, which grants the licences, the government said. A further fine of
Dollars 20,000 would be imposed for offices operating beyond expiry of their
licence.
Vietnam's chamber of commerce and industry says there are 964 representative
offices with 629 in the southern industrial hub of Ho Chi Minh City and the
rest in the capital, Hanoi. Most of those breaking the law are understood to
be small Asian companies.
</TEXT>
