<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / China's exports up by 31.2%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
China's exports continued to grow more strongly than imports in the seven
months to the end of July, indicating a smaller trade deficit for the year
than forecast, Tony Walker reports from Beijing. According to Chinese
customs statistics, exports reached Dollars 58.74bn (Pounds 39.1bn), an
increase of 31.2 per cent over the same period last year. Imports totalled
Dollars 58.81bn, up 19 per cent. In July exports grew much faster than
imports: they were up by 35.7 per cent compared with a rise in imports of
just 9.7 per cent.
This indicates imports continue to slow in response to tight restriction on
credit imposed in July last year and tightened in the early months of this
year.
China last year recorded a Dollars 12.2bn deficit on its trading account
compared with a surplus of Dollars 4.4bn in 1992. Chinese economists had
forecast a Dollars 10bn trade deficit this year, but it now seems likely it
will be less. Chinese customs reported that to the end of July, Japan was
China's largest trading partner, with bilateral trade reaching Dollars
23.15bn compared with Dollars 20.98bn for Hong Kong and Dollars 17.2bn for
the US.
</TEXT>
