<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Sri Lankan business fears poll upset
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MERVYN DE SILVA and STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COLOMBO, NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sri Lankan businessmen are bracing themselves for the possible defeat in
next week's general election of the ruling United National party which has
governed the country for 17 years.
They fear victory next Tuesday for the left-leaning opposition People's
Alliance, an eight-party coalition, could bring political and economic
uncertainty.
'Uppermost in the minds of most Sri Lankans in this election will
undoubtedly be the maintenance of political stability,' says the current
issue of the Sri Lanka Exporter, a pro-government business magazine.
The opposition parties have given public assurances that they would not
abandon the pro-market economic reforms carried out by the UNP over the past
three years. Mrs Chandrika Kumaratunge, the opposition leader, has called
for 'structural adjustment with a human face'. But businessmen fear her
allies, which include the Communist party, will demand more radical shifts
in economic policy.
Shares on the Colombo Stock Exchange fell sharply earlier this year when Mrs
Kumaratunge began attracting huge crowds at rallies. But it has since
stabilised.
The political uncertainty began in March with the ruling party's defeat in
March in provincial polls - the UNP's first electoral setback in 17 years.
Mr DB Wijetunga, who succeeded the assassinated president, Ranasinghe
Premadasa, last May, tried to win back support with a string of populist
financial hand-outs, including tax cuts and food-stamps for schoolchildren.
But he failed to take the steam out of the opposition, especially the
centrist Sri Lanka Freedom party, headed by Mrs Kumaratunge, the daughter of
Mrs Sirima Bandaranaike, the former prime minister.
The general election was not due to be held until next year, after a
presidential poll in November, but Mr Wijetunga has called an early general
election in the belief that the UNP will do better in a party-based contest
than in a head-to-head presidential battle between himself and Mrs
Kumaratunge.
The UNP in its campaign is reminding voters that, under Mrs Bandaranaike's
leftist government, the pre-UNP 1970s were for Sri Lanka 'an era of ration
cards, queues, quotas and shortages'. Mrs Kumaratunge, herself a generation
younger than Mr Wijetunga, appeals to voters who are too young to remember
the 1970s and who believe that 17 years in power is long enough for any
party.
Mrs Kumaratunge is also trying to exploit the fact that even though Sri
Lanka has successfully opened its economy to international trade and
investment, unemployment (standing at 12.6 per cent) and inflation (running
at an annual rate of 11.4 per cent) remain persistent problems.
</TEXT>
