<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Rail dispute set to worsen as union calls fresh strike: BR
chairman warns of 'dangerous' alternatives if stoppages continue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Both sides in the increasingly bitter rail signalling dispute blamed each
other's intransigence last night for the failure to reach a settlement as
the network faced its longest period of disruption since the conflict began
nine weeks ago.
The latest bout of disruption will affect an estimated 5m travellers around
this weekend. Today's stoppage ends at midnight. While the network will run
normally over tomorrow and Sunday, this will be followed by 48 hours of
strikes ending at midnight on Tuesday.
The RMT transport union executive yesterday announced that a further strike
by signal workers was planned from noon on Monday, August 22, to noon on
Tuesday, August 23.
Last night Railtrack, the state-owned infrastructure operator, said it hoped
that up to 37 per cent of the network would be open for services over the 72
hours of the present strike.
The two sides seem determined to persist with a battle of attrition in what
is now one of the longest industrial conflicts since the miners' strike of
1984-1985.
Last night Mr Jimmy Knapp, the RMT's general secretary, said he was
'bitterly disappointed' at what he described as 'yet another lost
opportunity' to settle the dispute. Railtrack's current offer of a 6 per
cent supplement plus a Pounds 250 lump sum payment was 'as unacceptable
today as it was four weeks ago when it was first made'.
'I hope the public will recognise all the initiatives to try and resolve the
dispute have come from the union. This weekend's disruption could have been
avoided if Railtrack had shown some realism and flexibility.
'Railtrack's stubbornness is losing them their holy grail of restructuring.
Without an agreement on RMT's claim, Railtrack are not going to get
agreement on restructuring.'
In a letter to Mr Knapp, Mr David Armstrong, Railtrack's industrial
relations director, accused the RMT of inflexibility and intransigence. He
said the union's peace proposals were not acceptable and warned that there
were 'only seven weeks' left to complete the restructuring deal for the
signal workers if the RMT was not to make them 'disadvantaged in pension
terms'.
He added: 'I don't need to remind you that September 30 is the last date for
new pay deals to be taken into account under the reshaping of the present
railway-wide pension scheme.'
Mr Armstrong called on the union to have five days of talks to hammer out a
final package for the signal workers.
Sir Bob Reid, chairman of British Rail which operates services, said
yesterday some of his staff could be called in to help operate signal boxes
if the dispute was not settled soon. BR would have 'no alternative but to
look for a different, much more dangerous solution'. He added: 'We have got
to help people to run the boxes. I don't want to see our business
disappear.'
It is estimated that about 100 BR staff are qualified to operate signal
boxes, but so far have not been asked to do so. BR said this was not likely
during the latest strikes. It was up to Railtrack to request help.
With the conflict deepening, Railtrack's options include the introduction of
individual contracts for signalling staff, but this is not being considered
immediately. It prefers to open more of the network while keeping pressure
on the union's members to persuade it to re-enter talks.
The company is concerned the RMT may call strikes over the August bank
holiday. But there is no sign of the union contemplating such action, which
could destroy public support.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Railtrack.
    British Rail.
</CO>
<XX>
