<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Rate rises in Sweden and Italy hit European markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, PHILIP GAWITH and ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Surprise interest rate rises in Italy and Sweden threw European financial
markets into turmoil yesterday and triggered speculation other continental
central banks might follow suit.
The Bank of Italy raised two short-term rates, with the key discount rate
increasing from 7 per cent to 7.5 per cent. In Sweden, the Riksbank raised
its lending rate to banks from 7.5 per cent to 8 per cent, and the important
money market repurchase rate from 6.92 per cent to 7.2 per cent.
Although the moves by the two central banks were widely seen to be motivated
by domestic concerns, they sent shock waves through European bond markets
because some investors saw them as confirmation that continental interest
rates were on the rise.
The move was also felt in the US currency market where the dollar ended
sharply lower against other leading currencies on similar expectations of
rising European rates.
Markets are also nervous ahead of next week's meeting of the US Federal
Reserve's open market committee, which many expect to lead to higher US
interest rates.
The Bank of Italy also increased its Lombard, or fixed-term advances, rate
from 8 per cent to 8.5 per cent, citing the need to defend the lira from
speculative attack. However, initially the change was counter-productive.
Yesterday evening, the lira was quoted at a record low of L1,016.50 against
the D-Mark, compared with a London close of L1,005 10 minutes before the
rate move was announced.
The Riksbank said its move was designed to counter inflationary pressures.
However, the foreign exchange markets were unimpressed, saying that both
central banks had failed to address the main issue worrying the markets -
the large fiscal deficits of the two countries.
The Swedish krona was quoted in London at SKr4.987 against the D-Mark, off a
low of SKr5 earlier in the day, but well below Wednesday's close of
SKr4.940.
Ms Alison Cottrell, international economist at Midland Global Markets,
stressed the detrimental impact of the moves. 'Putting up rates doesn't make
your currency stronger . . . and it will be harder for the governments to
fund,' she said. She cited the case of the Italian national debt, much of
which is financed on a short-term basis. Yesterday's change would add
L3,000bn (Pounds 1.2bn) to the cost of debt service in the first year.
European markets were surprised by the changes although Mr Keith Skeoch,
chief economist at James Capel, said the rate rises were a 'timely reminder
that we are close to the turning point in world interest rates'.
Mr Sanjay Joshi of Daiwa Europe said markets reacted badly over 'the fear
that some of the smaller central banks will be forced to follow suit'.
Bond prices, which tend to move in the opposite direction to interest rates,
fell sharply. In Italy, 10-year government bonds lost 2.6 points, pushing
the yield to 11.26 per cent from 10.77 per cent on Wednesday. The yield on
Swedish nine-year bonds rose by just over half a percentage point to 11.28
per cent.
In the UK, the price of 10-year gilts fell 1 1/2 points, pushing the yield
to 8.67 per cent from 8.42 per cent, while in Germany, the yield on 10-year
bunds rose to 7.20 per cent from 7 per cent.
Rate rise details, Page 2; Letter, Page 12; Lex, Page 14; Bonds, Page 20;
Currencies, Page 23; World stocks, Page 29
</TEXT>
