<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / International Capital Markets: Pinault's plan to take over
Fnac hits snag
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Francois Pinault, the French entrepreneur, yesterday hit a snag in his
plans to take control of Fnac, the retailing group, when Compagnie Generale
des Eaux, one of the existing shareholders, delayed a decision on exercising
its pre-emptive rights over the shares.
Artemis, the company that controls Mr Pinault's family interests, last month
struck a deal with Altus Finance, a subsidiary of the troubled Credit
Lyonnais banking group, to buy the latter's 64.6 per cent shareholding in
Fnac for just under FFr2bn (Dollars 370m)
However, Generale des Eaux, the utility and media group that last year
joined forces with Altus to acquire Fnac from the ailing GMF insurance
company, has pre-emptive rights over the holding. Under the terms of the
deal, Generale des Eaux has a month to decide whether to exercise those
rights.
Generale des Eaux yesterday said Altus had agreed that it could postpone its
decision for another week.
Generale des Eaux, which was originally expected not to exercise its
pre-emptive rights, refused to comment on whether it was now considering
doing so.
Mr Pinault, who has in recent years emerged as one of France's most
aggressive businessmen by building up the powerful Pinault-Printemps
retailing empire, must also secure the French finance ministry's agreement
to complete his attempted takeover of Fnac, which dominates the French music
and books market.
