<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / International Company News: TWA makes further management
reshuffle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWA, the seventh biggest US carrier, yesterday signalled the launch of an
attempt to stave off a looming financial crisis and restore the struggling
airline to profitability.
Announcing the latest in a series of management changes, it said the new
management team had 120 days to achieve three business goals: to produce a
new business plan, secure new labour agreements with its unions, and to
negotiate a restructuring of its debts.
TWA emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in November last year but
has not made a profit since. All its credit facilities are drawn, virtually
all its assets are pledged, and it has insufficient cash to repay Dollars
190m worth of debt falling due for repayment in January.
Last week it announced that it was shedding 500 jobs immediately and up to
2,500 more within 30 days. It also announced the closure of its operations
in Geneva and Zurich, Switzerland, and the suspension of polar flights
between Los Angeles and Paris for the winter.
Yesterday it said it had promoted Mr Jeffrey Erickson from chief operating
officer to chief executive. Mr Donald Craib, previously chairman and chief
executive, remains chairman. Mr Robert Peiser, a former TWA manager now
working for a consultancy, returns to the vacant post of chief financial
officer.
Mr Erickson said the business plan inherited from TWA's Chapter 11
reorganisation was 'not realistic' and another would be finished within two
weeks. The company was also involved in discussions with union leaders over
new labour agreements.
United Airlines of the US and National Airlines of Chile said they had
signed a marketing agreement including code-sharing arrangements and joint
frequent-flier benefits, initially applying to flights in and out of the
Chilean cities of Arica and Antofagasta.
</TEXT>
