<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / Elderly give approval to health reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Endorsements and rejections flew thick and fast yesterday, as the US Senate
entered its second day of what was still mostly civilised debate on
healthcare reform.
Supporters of the bills proposed by the Democratic leaders in both chambers
of Congress were grateful for the strong backing of the American Association
of Retired People, representing 33m people.
The AARP, though long sympathetic to the Clinton administration's broad
approach, had not endorsed any bill. It warned: 'If either bill is defeated,
healthcare reform will be dead for years.'
The version sponsored by Senator George Mitchell, the Senate majority
leader, also secured the qualified approval of the Congressional Budget
Office. It found that the Mitchell bill would 'slightly reduce the federal
budget deficit', but expanded insurance coverage would 'add to national
health care expenditures' in the aggregate.
The CBO calculated that Mr Mitchell's proposed subsidies to the poor and
small businesses would cost Dollars 420bn (Pounds 272bn) by 2000 and Dollars
1,100bn by 2004, but that this could be more than offset by higher taxes on
such as cigarettes and by savings on the Medicaid programme for the
indigent.
It thought his goal of 95 per cent insurance coverage could be achieved
earlier than its target date of 2000, but it raised doubts about his
subsidies. It said these would be vulnerable in the event of an increase in
the budget deficit.
On the other side, big and small businesses lined up to fight the Mitchell
bill. But attempts on the Senate floor to delay debate, instigated by
Senator Jesse Helms, the right-wing Republican from North Carolina, were
voted down.
For much of yesterday, senators tried to maintain the tone of debate
established on Monday night by the two principal protagonists, Senator
Mitchell and Senator Robert Dole, the Republican minority leader.
his political toughness. He has, after all, threatened to keep the Senate
sit ting throughout the summer, if necessary, to complete action on his
bill.
Mr Mitchell kept insisting that his proposals were there to be improved
upon. Healthcare reform was 'a matter of simple justice', its purpose 'the
wellbeing of American families', the approach of his bill essentially
'voluntary', with 'nothing political' in it.
Mr Dole repeated three times the Republican mantra: 'America has the best
healthcare system in the world'. But he, too, offered conciliation of a
kind: 'We believe there is a lot in our bill, a lot in Senator Mitchell's
bill, a lot in other bills. We could go in a back room and in two or three
days get a bill that could pass 99 to one.'
</TEXT>
