<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Standard weak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The worst individual performance in the FT-SE 100 came from Standard
Chartered, the banking group, whose shares fell almost 6 per cent in spite
of top of the range half-year profits. The market was concerned about
pressures on margins in the group's Hong Kong business, a factor which also
took its toll of HSBC shares. The latter is scheduled to report interims on
Monday.
One dealer said Standard's underlying figures were 'OK but unspectacular;
the lack of good news at the analysts' meeting put more pressure on the
shares'. At the close Standard shares were 16 down at 259p, having touched a
day's low of 255p. Turnover of 9.4m shares was the highest single day's
business since mid-June. HSBC Holdings fell 16 1/2 to 778p on volume of
5.8m.
Lloyds Bank rose 6 to 555p ahead of a press conference called for this
morning at which Lloyds will give details of its revised offer for the
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society.
Turnover in British Steel rose to 16m, making it the day's most active
stock, and the shares firmed 2 1/2 to 164 1/2 p as sentiment was boosted by
favourable results from Dutch steel group Hoogovens.
Engineering concern GKN advanced 6 to 657p in trade of 3.2m as brokers
upgraded full-year profits expectations after it reported interim figures
ahead of the best market forecasts.
Profits jumped 62 per cent to Pounds 97m, with analysts impressed by the
rise given the small increase in sales and improvement in margins in the
automotive division.
The list of brokers upgrading included Mr Robert Speed at Henderson
Crosthwaite, a long time bull of the stock. He raised his full-year forecast
by Pounds 22m to Pounds 190m, while NatWest Securities lifted its estimate
by Pounds 28m to Pounds 205m.
A Smith New Court recommendation continued to support Rolls-Royce, which
closed 5 ahead at 201p.
Profit-taking in Transport Development Group left the shares 8 adrift at
227p, after the company reported improved first-half figures.
Marketing services group WPP declined 3 1/2 to 119 1/2 p on profit-taking
following figures at the high end of expectations. The market is awaiting an
injection of 190m shares into the market as the banks which bailed out the
group two years ago unwind the rest of their debt-for-equity swap.
Positive comment on Courtaulds' fibre operations and talk of a
recommendation by Robert Fleming Securities saw the shares add 10 at 548p.
The soap detergent war between household products groups Procter &amp; Gamble
and Unilever hit Hickson International as it announced first-half figures.
Hickson makes Accelerator, the bleach ingredient at the centre of the
washing powder wrangle. The shares retreated 9 to 168p.
International conglomerate Hanson added 3 1/4 at 266 3/4 p following a
detailed analysis of the group in conjnunction with BTR, Williams Holdings
and Tomkins from Credit Lyonnais Laing. The research looks at prospects for
the groups in the US and highlights Hanson as offering the best value. BTR
and Williams were flat at 387p and 370p respectively. Tomkins gained 1 1/2
at 236p.
The recent strong showing by Bass prompted a couple of switch
recommendations, with Whitbread being the chief beneficiary. Hoare Govett
and James Capel were said to be recommending the move to clients. Bass
declined 7 to 563p on 1.3m shares traded, while Whitbread managed a rise of
11 to 543p on turnover of 2.1m. Scottish &amp; Newcastle suffered from similar
moves, the shares dipping 4 to 523p.
The hot weather showed through to soft drink sales at JN Nicols (Vimto) and
the shares gained 3 at 233p. Interim profits increased from Pounds 3.40m to
Pounds 3.76m. Other statistics, Page 29
</TEXT>
