<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Program buying helps Dow to
modest rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Early computerised program buying, strong demand for technology shares and a
moderately successful auction of new government securities in the bond
market helped US equity prices post modest gains across the board yesterday,
writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 11.00 at 3,766.76. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 gained 2.37 at 460.30, while the
American Stock Exchange composite finished 1.75 higher at 443.97 and the
Nasdaq composite 5.60 ahead at 728.21. Trading volume on the New York SE
totalled 279.5m shares.
As during the first two days of the week, there was little interest in
buying stocks among retail investors at the opening yesterday, primarily
because they were waiting for a lead from the bond market, which was in the
middle of digesting billions of dollars of new government securities.
The second leg of the Treasury's quarterly refunding round - the sale of
Dollars 12bn in 10-year notes - was due during the afternoon, and bond
prices were subdued ahead of the auction. Share prices were also little
changed, but some selected program buying helped stocks edge higher at
mid-morning.
Prices held on to their gains later in the day when the 10-year auction
passed off uneventfully, with demand from investors for the new paper
slightly stronger than expected.
Sentiment, however, stayed unsettled, primarily because of concern about the
July inflation data. The figures, due out today and tomorrow, are nervously
awaited by the markets because, if inflation is shown to be gathering pace,
the Federal Reserve could decide to sanction another interest rate increase.
Such a move would depress stock prices, although growing expectations of
another monetary policy tightening mean that the impact of a rate increase
has partly already been priced into the market.
Technology shares were in demand for the second consecutive day, with Texas
Instruments climbing Dollars 3 7/8 to Dollars 84 1/8 , Hewlett-Packard
Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 82 1/4 and Compaq Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 35 1/8 .
Procter&amp;Gamble, which reported a 24 per cent jump in second-quarter
underlying earnings yesterday, advanced Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 54 7/8 .
Among the biggest losers of the day was Dillard Department Stores. Shares in
the retailer dropped Dollars 4 7/8 to Dollars 26 5/8 in volume of 3.9m as
investors reacted harshly to news of second-quarter earnings that were below
market expectations.
Reports that Kidder, Peabody, the troubled Wall Street investment bank, lost
between Dollars 50m and Dollars 60m in the month of July, mostly because of
problems in the mortgage-backed securities market, unsettled the shares of
its parent group, General Electric, which shed Dollars 3/4 to Dollars 48 1/8
in heavy trade.
On the Nasdaq market, Lotus forged ahead Dollars 4 5/8 to Dollars 40 1/4 in
volume of 4.1m shares after the company said that it was entering into a
world-wide marketing and product development pact with leading chipmaker
Intel. The latter put on Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 59 3/4 .
Canada
Toronto finished solidly higher, supported by recent strength in the
Canadian dollar. The TSE 300 index closed above 4,200 with a rise of 18.3 at
4,205.1. Advances outpaced falls by 389 to 304 after volume of 62.2m shares.
Eleven of the 14 sub-indices were higher, led by transportation, up 1.5 per
cent. Financial services and industrial products each rose 1.2 per cent.
Nova firmed CDollars 1/2 to CDollars 13 1/2 on the day's heaviest volume of
some 5.8m shares. The company attributed the strong interest in its stock
partly to an explosion earlier this week at an ethylene plant of Exxon, a
key competitor of Nova in the US ethylene market.
Mexico
Stocks ended moderately easier, with profit-taking continuing to determine
market movement. Traders said short-term investors sold off shares for the
third successive session, with not even a cut in primary interest rates
giving much support to the market.
A 65 basis-point fall in the bellwether 28-day Cetes rate to 15.15 per cent
at the weekly auction yesterday boosted shares only briefly in opening
transactions. Equities soon moved into reverse as profit-taking dominated
transactions, and falling prices of New York-traded American Depositary
Receipts (ADRs) of Mexican blue chips also dragged the local market down.
The IPC index lost 20.29 at 2,574.67.
</TEXT>
