<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / No longer the faithful followers of the family: Hugh Carnegy
finds Swedish institutions getting tough
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The snub dealt this week by Swedish institutions to Charter, the UK
industrial group, over its bid for Esab, the world's leading supplier of
welding equipment, was a strong reminder that minority shareholders in
Sweden are no longer content to play the role of faithful followers to big
owners such as the Wallenberg family.
The rejection by five institutions of a Pounds 260m bid, recommended by the
Esab board, carried echoes of the shareholder revolt which last December
blocked the merger between Volvo and France's Renault - to date the most
spectacular flexing of Swedish institutional muscle.
This week it was the turn of the Wallenberg empire to suffer an
institutional rebuff - albeit a much less violent one. Esab has been
controlled by the Wallenbergs through the industrial group Incentive. In
June, Incentive accepted Charter's offer of SKr345 per share for its near 50
per cent stake with alacrity to help pay for its SKr8.4bn (Pounds 700m)
takeover of Cardo, an industrial investment offshoot of Volvo. But Esab's
share price then shot up, wiping out the 20 per cent premium in Charter's
offer.
When Esab's strong half-year results sent the share price even higher this
week, institutional shareholders decided the bid was underpriced. Incentive
and Charter, on the other hand, still insist that the offer is fair.
It was not the first time this year that institutions have held out against
Incentive. In June, three Cardo shareholders objected to the original terms
for the Incentive takeover of shares not held by Volvo and won a revision of
the bid.
A non-Swedish investment banker involved in the Volvo-Renault negotiations
says the days of 'sweetheart deals done in the sauna - and never mind the
other shareholders' are over. 'You have to demonstrate to shareholders that
you have done everything right.'
Analysts in Stockholm say the Wallenbergs have taken this on board. It would
no longer be possible to push through a deal like that in 1991, when they
shifted Incentive out of Asea, forcing minority shareholders to accept a
dilution of their stake in the half-owner of the Swedish-Swiss combine Asea
Brown Boveri.
In Charter's case, the UK company appears to have miscalculated the extent
to which Swedish institutions now defend their interests. Having reached
agreement with the Esab board and Incentive, Charter executives proclaimed
that the rising Esab share price - usually on low volumes - was nothing more
than a brazen attempt to squeeze more out of the bidder. When Mr Jeffrey
Herbert, Charter's chief executive, and colleagues arrived in Stockholm on
Tuesday, they were met by a series of public announcements of bid
rejections. This snookered Charter, which needed 90 per cent acceptances.
Undoubtedly, a perception among the shareholders that Charter was behaving
arrogantly did not help. This, and a trade union campaign portraying Charter
as an unwelcome foreign predator, was also reminiscent of the more
hysterical moments in the Volvo-Renault affair. The institutions insist
their objections lie simply in the bid price.
In the case of the Renault merger, the institutions did have strategic
objections to the plan to shift Volvo's core car and truck making operations
under the wing of a state-owned French company. 'Since then the
consciousness of the ownership role we play has risen substantially,' said a
senior institutional shareholder.
But the new-found assertiveness of the institutions has mainly applied to
deal terms, rather than seeking real influence over corporate strategy. The
power exercised by the Wallenbergs over their companies - often through less
than majority stakes - has not been seriously challenged.
