<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / Review sets the scene for cutting and dealing: Michael Smith
finds the Recs poised for a bout of change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Regional electricity companies (Recs) in England and Wales are expected to
undergo a series of profound changes, with takeovers among the
possibilities, following publication today of the industry regulator's
pricing review.
Takeover talks and stake building could begin within weeks, according to
some analysts. The 12 Recs in England and Wales have a market value of about
Pounds 15bn, while their two Scottish counterparts - the review of which
will be completed later this year - total Pounds 4.6bn.
The review covers the distribution business, which provides the companies
withof their annual profits. While the regulator has been scrutinising the
sector, plans for change have often been put on hold. So whatever his
conclusions, the review's completion should trigger activity. The Recs are
likely to:
consider acquisitions to help transform them into more broadly based utility
groups;
make more job cuts and changes to working practices. Staff cuts of 10-25 per
cent have been common in the four years since privatisation; decide what to
do with the National Grid, the transmission company which they own. Valued
at Pounds 4bn-Pounds 5bn, it is expected to be floated on the London Stock
Exchange next spring.
Some of the companies will become bid targets. Their attractions include
their financial strength - most have net cash or low borrowings - and their
conservative accounting. New management might see the potential for reducing
tax charges and releasing provisions made for eventualities which may never
happen. Several companies, for example, put aside money years ago to cater
for the possible adverse effects of a European Court ruling on pensions.
Potential predators, or suitors, include overseas utilities groups and
UK-based conglomerates. However, it is also possible that some of the Recs
will get together voluntarily.
Some analysts believe Scottish Power and Northern Electric would make a good
fit. Others mentioned as potential takeover candidates tend to be the
smaller concerns such as Manweb, Seeboard, South Wales Electricity and South
Western Electricity.
Obstacles to deals are likely to include the unwillingness of managements to
give up their power bases. Since the City rates most of the companies
similarly, it is unlikely that one of the Recs will go for another without
prior agreement. Any contested bid is likely to come from outside.
The second obstacle is the government's ownership of a 'golden share' in
each company. This limits other stakes to a maximum of 15 per cent. However,
the government has shown flexibility in the past and, in any case, the
golden shares expire in the English and Welsh companies next March.
This puts pressure on the companies to reform from within. One way of
lessening attractions to a hostile bidder would be to unlock hidden value
before a predator points to it. Flotation of the National Grid is an obvious
example.
The Recs could also make themselves less digestible to some predators by
making large acquisitions.
Norweb and Yorkshire Electricity have already made overseas purchases. Other
companies are likely to tread cautiously, partly because of City wariness
about utility companies' diversification. For that reason the companies may
prefer to concentrate on improving internal efficiency.
