<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / Procter &amp; Gamble up 24% in quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Procter &amp; Gamble, the US consumer products group, reported a 24 per cent
surge in underlying fourth-quarter profits, helped by a 7 per cent rise in
the volume of goods sold and lower costs.
Net earnings in the three months to June were Dollars 406m (Pounds 262m)
compared with an underlying Dollars 327m last time - though the figure
reported last year was a loss of Dollars 1.55m because of restructuring
charges.
Turnover was up 2 per cent at Dollars 7.5bn. The company said the rise would
have been 4 per cent but for shifts in exchange rates and lower pricing.
Earnings per share were 56 cents against last year's underlying 44 cents.
Mr Edwin Artzt, chairman and chief executive, said the results reflected
significant progress in cost reduction objectives, along with a unit volume
growth of 7 per cent worldwide.
For the year as a whole, net profits were affected by the Dollars 102m
charge taken in April to cover losses on an ill-fated foray into
derivatives.
This left net earnings at Dollars 2.21bn, or Dollars 2.91 a share. The
previous year, the company made net profits of Dollars 2.02bn, or Dollars
2.81 a share, before the restructuring charge.
'This was a good year, and if not for the derivatives loss, it would have
been a great year,' said Mr Artzt.
Soap wars may affect Hickson, Page 17
