<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There seems to be a belief in television that if a thing is worth doing, it
is worth doing over and over again. Or is it just a question of being
pre-empted by your competitors? On Saturday BBC1 showed the first of a
two-part documentary about Hammer horror films. Today Channel 4 begins a
series called The World Of Hammer which runs for 13 episodes, no less
(12.25). A few weeks ago Channel 4 ran a long sequence of programmes about
the troubles in Northern Ireland. Now BBC2 is running a long sequence on the
same topic. Today we are offered a 10-minute look at 'some of the surprising
economic factors', Consequences; and a 40-minute look at comedians in
Northern Ireland, The Empire Laughs Back (11.15). Have there not been
previous programmes showing the activity inside a blue tit's box as the nest
is lined, the eggs laid and the demanding chicks fed? Was there not a whole
series of programmes including just such material quite recently from the
BBC's Bristol unit?  So why is Channel 4 beginning another run of Wild
Britain with life inside a blue tit's box? (8.30).
