FT  11 AUG 94 / Portillo plan 'could damage Tory vote'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday claimed that Mr Michael Portillo, the employment secretary,
could severely damage the Conservatives' chances in the next general
election if his call for a cut in state support for industry is implemented.
Mr Frank Dobson, Labour's acting campaign manager, strongly attacked Mr
Portillo for showing with his recent call for a reduction in the Department
of Trade and Industry's budget that 'he was out of touch with the real
world'.
The attack coincided with claims by Mr Derek Fatchett, shadow industry
minister, that 182 Tory MPs could lose their seats if the DTI is forced to
scale back its programme of regional assistance in the way Mr Portillo
recently demanded in a letter to Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and
industry secretary.
'Mr Portillo's proposals are a direct attack on his own party's MPs,' said
Mr Fatchett. 'But more importantly, they will hurt British business. His
colleagues must now decide whether to back their local industries or sack Mr
Portillo.'
