<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / Women amid 'male camaraderie': A look at moves to counter
sexual discrimination in the office
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Miss Samantha Phillips, the insurance broker who yesterday won her case of
sexual discrimination and unfair dismissal against Willis Corroon, did not,
in the end, convince the industrial tribunal that she had been sexually
harassed by her manager on a business trip.
Nonetheless the case has served to highlight the difficulties of women who
work in what the tribunal yesterday described as 'an atmosphere of male
camaraderie'.
Sexual harassment has become a high-profile issue - treated increasingly
seriously by large employers - since 1986 when it was recognised as an
offence under the Sex Discrimination Act.
Organisations as diverse as the European Commission, British
Telecommunications and Goldman Sachs have made offenders leave following
complaints of harassment.
Publicity surrounding the issue has encouraged increasing numbers of women -
and a handful of men - to complain. Last year the Equal Opportunities
Commission received 793 complaints about sexual harassment, 58 per cent up
on the previous year. The commission believes this is 'the tip of the
iceberg'.
Ms Jayne Monkhouse, head of the commission's employment practices unit,
said: 'People make a claim of sexual harassment when they are at their wits'
end. A lot of women suffer a low level of harassment, such as persistent
name calling, pin-ups or pornography on their computers, which they try to
put up with.'
Surveys suggest that a majority of women suffer some form of sexual
harassment at work. When the Industrial Society surveyed 1,727 men and women
last year, 45 per cent said they had experienced some form of sexual
harassment. Nine out of 10 of the complaints were from women.
The commission believes women are most vulnerable where they are in a
minority, such as in the fire service or police. They also receive a
disproportionate number of complaints from women in small organisations,
where managers or owners of the business are often the culprits.
Large organisations are taking the issue increasingly seriously. Nearly all
public-sector employers and a majority of the largest private-sector
employers have policies to deal with sexual harassment.
Part of the impetus for these policies is that their existence will provide
some protection should the company be taken to an industrial tribunal.
Companies are potentially exposed to large claims following the European
Court's removal of the Pounds 11,000 ceiling on compensation for sexual
discrimination last year.
Most company policies are in line with the European Commission code of
practice issued three years ago. This recommends that companies put out a
clear statement of principle condemning all harassment, train managers to
deal with problems, and set up informal and formal avenues for investigating
complaints and disciplining culprits.
Few UK companies go as far as many US businesses, which sometimes adopt
blanket prohibitions on employees touching or dating colleagues.
Nonetheless, many companies issue comprehensive guidelines.
Midland Bank, for instance, sends staff a three-monthly circular reminding
them of the definition of sexual harassment. Its definition of unacceptable
behaviour includes 'staring and leering', pin-ups, unsolicited and unwanted
gifts, the use of explicit language, unwanted propositions, deliberate body
contact, groping and fondling.
Complaints at the bank are investigated by staff from an unrelated
department. If a preliminary inquiry finds grounds for suspicion, the
accused staff member is suspended while a full inquiry takes place. If found
guilty, the employee will be dismissed.
In practice, implementation of anti-harassment policies does not always live
up to the theory. Mr Michael Rubenstein, editor of Equal Opportunities
Review, said: 'The big problem now is going from paper to practice.'
Problems often arise when companies decide to move one of the employees.
Since most cases involve an offender who is senior to the victim, companies
are often inclined to transfer the victim. Mr Rubenstein said this would
deter people from coming forward. 'If the complainant is punished for the
behaviour of the harasser, it may undercut the whole policy.'
The attitude of the employer is crucial. Many women still fear that they
will be pilloried or ostracised if they complain. The fear of humiliating
publicity associated with a tribunal hearing is a strong deterrent to
seeking legal redress.
In spite of the growing commitment by large employers to tackle the
problems, many employees still feel they have no option but to suffer it.
The weak state of the job market has worsened the problems, according to Ms
Monkhouse. 'People often put up with behaviour when in a more fluid job
market they would just walk out.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
