<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / Thomson attacks agents on discounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thomson, Britain's largest tour operator, yesterday attacked travel agents
selling its holidays at lower discounts than they offer on rival operators'
products.
Mr Charles Newbold, Thomson's managing director, said agents which offered
larger discounts on other operators' holidays would suffer as consumers
looked elsewhere.
Mr Newbold said his group would not tolerate any challenge to its market
dominance. 'We wish to make it clear that our position in the marketplace is
not negotiable. Anybody who attempts to usurp that position we would regard
as unwelcome.'
The three largest travel retail chains are offering discounts of up to 15
per cent on summer 1995 holidays. Lunn Poly, which is owned by Thomson, is
selling all its holidays at a 15 per cent discount.
Going Places and Thomas Cook, the second and third-largest chains
respectively, are offering 15 per cent discounts on holidays from Airtours
and Owners Abroad, but only 5 per cent on Thomson packages. Going Places is
owned by Airtours; Thomas Cook has financial links with Owners Abroad.
Mr Newbold said: 'Going Places is not a retailer of holidays. It is an
outlet for Airtours.'
Mr Kevin Welch, Going Places' marketing director, said his chain was
offering lower discounts on Thomson holidays because Thomson paid it a lower
commission of only 10 per cent.
Mr Welch denied Going Places acted merely as an outlet for Airtours'
holidays. He said Thomson's share of Lunn Poly's business was higher than
Airtours' share of Going Places' business.
Thomas Cook also said its discounts reflected the level of commission it
received from tour operators.
Thomson said it intended to sell its summer 1995 holidays at this year's
prices. The average cost of a summer 1995 holiday would be Pounds 350, the
same as this year and lower than the 1993 figure of Pounds 375.
</TEXT>
