</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A further 207 job losses were yesterday announced at Swan Hunter, the
Tyneside shipbuilder, Chris Tighe writes. The redundancies affect workers
laid off since May 31.
The receivers injected a new urgency to the struggle to find a buyer for the
company by insisting that unless Constructions Mecaniques de Normandie - the
sole prospective bidder for the yard as a going concern - starts paying the
Pounds 200,000-a-month wage bill of the technical and design team by the end
of August, the team's 100 members will also be made redundant.
Price Waterhouse says talks with CMN have not yet yielded a deal. Mr Fred
Henderson of CMN insisted yesterday that the French company had an
'understanding' with the receivers, and that a deal hinged on the Ministry
of Defence agreeing to CMN's proposal to take on the contract for Swans'
last frigate, which is scheduled for completion in November, and
sub-contract it to the receiver.
