FT  11 AUG 94 / Mexicans 'will protest' if election fraudulent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mexico's rebel-organised 'democratic convention' in the jungle ended with
delegates promising massive civil disobedience and protests if there is
fraud in the presidential election on August 21 but rejecting an armed
uprising, writes Damian Fraser in Mexico City.
The convention, which ended on Tuesday, was hosted by the Zapatista Army of
National Liberation in the Lacandon jungle of the southern state of Chiapas.
Some 5,000 delegates from radical and leftist political organisations
throughout Mexico participated.
Sub-Comandante Marcos, the rebel spokesman, told delegates that the
Zapatistas would not be the first to take up arms. They launched a rebellion
in Chiapas in January and still control jungle areas.
The delegates left the jungle pledging to organise meetings and protests in
favour of a free vote on August 21. They said they would participate in the
elections, and vote against the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party.
Most are expected to vote for Mr Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, presidential candidate
of the main leftist opposition.
Mr Ernesto Zedillo of the ruling party holds a commanding lead over his
nearest rivals, according to a well-regarded national opinion poll. His
support stood at 46 per cent, against 19 per cent for Mr Diego Fernandez de
Cevallos of the centre-right opposition, and 9 per cent for Mr Cardenas,
with 18 per cent undecided.
