<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / TB/HIV epidemic 'could hit Asia'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   YOKOHAMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
As many as 12m lives could be saved in developing countries during the next
decade if the industrialised world increased annual spending on tuberculosis
programmes by between Dollars 100m (Pounds 66.6m) and Dollars 150m, the
World Health Organisation said yesterday.
The world's foreign aid agencies spend only Dollars 16m a year on
controlling TB. The WHO itself spent only Dollars 7m on its TB programme
this year.
Yet it can cost as little as Dollars 13 to cure someone of the disease, Dr
Arata Kochi, programme manager of the WHO's tuberculosis programme, told the
10th international conference on Aids in Yokohama.
TB and HIV threatened to combine to create a huge epidemic in Asia that
would dwarf that sweeping Africa and other parts of the world, said Dr
Kochi.
Annual TB/HIV deaths in Asia would surpass Africa by the end of the decade,
he added.
Over the next 10 years, the cost to the Asian economies of the Aids epidemic
alone could reach Dollars 52bn, according to the WHO.
Dr Tadao Shimao, president of the Japan Anti-Tuberculosis Association, said
that over the same period TB and Aids together would kill more people in
Asia than the numbers equal to the combined populations of the cities of
Singapore, Beijing, Yokohama and Tokyo.
About a third of the world's population carried the TB bacilli, although
most never become ill, said Dr Kochi.
However, an HIV-positive person was 30 times more likely to develop TB than
a non-infected individual, and was then capable of passing TB to
non-HIV-positive family and friends.
'This raises the frightening prospect that the general population now no
longer has nothing to fear from close proximity to HIV-positive people. They
are at risk (of contracting TB) simply by breathing the same air as
(HIV-positive) people with TB,' warned Dr Shimao.
The WHO estimated that in some parts of Asia, such as Thailand, India and
Nepal, as many as 70 per cent of Aids patients develop TB.
The median life-expectancy of an HIV-positive TB patient is six months. TB
already kills nearly 2m every year in Asia.
The organisation estimates that an additional package of between Dollars
1.5bn and Dollars 2.9bn would be required each year to set up and maintain a
basic programme for HIV prevention.
Funding for the WHO's Global Programme on Aids has fallen from a peak of
Dollars 90m a year to only Dollars 70m in 1994.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QQZ  Developing Countries.
</CN>
