<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / Kok cabinet to be named soon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Dutch caretaker finance minister, Mr Wim Kok, was yesterday putting the
finishing touches to a three-party government coalition agreement that will
make him the next prime minister, more than 100 days after the May general
election. The three parties that are aiming to govern - Mr Kok's Labour
party, the right-wing Liberals and the left-of-centre D66 - will be asked to
approve the plan over the next few days, and ministers are expected to be
appointed next week. The proposed left-right coalition, a new departure in
Dutch politics, will relegate the Christian Democrats of prime minister Ruud
Lubbers to the opposition benches for the first time in modern Dutch
politics. Mr Kok's plan calls for Fl 18bn (Pounds 6.59bn) in spending cuts
over four years, around a third of them falling controversially on social
security. University education is also set for a shake-up. Students would
continue to receive funding up to their bachelor's degree, but would have to
take out loans to finance master's and doctoral degrees.
