<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / Fall in Russian output forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A 35-38 per cent decline this year in Russia's industrial production was
predicted in a central bank report this week. However, because industry
accounts for a decreasing portion of the economy, gross national product was
expected to fall by only 10 per cent. The report, the bank's annual public
declaration of its goals, sets a target of reducing inflation to 8 per cent
a month by the end of the year. Earlier this year the Russian central bank,
whose chairman was once an enthusiastic provider of soft credits to the
country's industry and agriculture, has since tightened its monetary policy
considerably. This has had moderate success in reining in runaway inflation,
but the economy now faces a new inflationary threat. Unable to easily obtain
credits from the government, Russian enterprises have extended loans to one
another, creating a growing mountain of debt which threatens to paralyse the
financial system. In this week's report the central bank suggests that
commercial banks should be asked to participate in the increasingly urgent
efforts of the Russian government to find a solution to the issue of
inter-enterprise debt.
</TEXT>
