<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / Cuts promised in electricity prices: Consumer bills set to
fall by Pounds 2.5bn over five years under power revenue controls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Savings totalling Pounds 2.5bn for electricity users in England and Wales
over the next five years will be promised today by the industry's regulator
as he unveils price controls that are likely to disappoint consumer groups
but please investors.
Prof Stephen Littlechild, director-general of the regulatory body Offer,
says his proposals imply reductions of Pounds 12-Pounds 16 in average
household electricity bills in the year from next April. This is equivalent
to at least 4 per cent.
The controls will cut allowed charges in the 12 regional electricity
companies' distribution businesses by 11-17 per cent in the year from April
1995, or an average of about 14 per cent, and will restrict price rises to 2
percentage points below inflation in each of the following four years.
Distribution charges make up more than a quarter of the typical electricity
bill.
Analysts were last night predicting that share prices of most of the 12
companies would rise since the controls were less severe than many had
feared.
Most believe it unlikely that any of the companies will challenge the price
formulae through the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
Prof Littlechild's price restrictions represent a significant tightening of
the controls that have been in place since the industry's privatisation four
years ago. The controls have allowed the regional companies to increase
distribution charges by up to 2.5 per cent above the rate of inflation.
Leaked letters from Prof Littlechild's office in the spring prompted
analysts to suggest that allowed charges could be cut by as much as 30 per
cent next April with rises in subsequent years restricted to inflation minus
4 percentage points.
In his 118-page report, to be released today, Prof Littlechild says
tightening of the controls will lead to savings of about Pounds 70-Pounds 90
over the five-year period for the average household.
The Pounds 2.5bn he says will result from the control changes will be shared
by all consumers, including large companies.
Prof Littlechild also argues that the companies whose allowed revenue will
fall by 17 per cent in the first year will then be on the equivalent of an
inflation minus 7.5 percentage points formula over each year of the
five-year period.
The companies suffering an initial 14 per cent reduction in allowable
revenue will be on the annual equivalent of inflation minus 6.5 percentage
points, and those suffering 11 per cent cuts will be on the equivalent of
inflation minus 5.5 points.
Electricity companies will use these figures to argue that their formula is
one of the toughest reviews by a regulator.
But consumer organisations and opposition parties are likely to feel the
controls fail to redress the balance between power users and shareholders
who have benefited from profit growth.
The stock market is initially likely to identify Manweb in north-west
England, Newcastle-based Northern Electric and Swalec in south Wales as the
losers since their allowed revenues are being cut by 17 per cent.
Scene set for cutting, Page 15
Pay-off for Manweb chief, Page 5
