<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 94 / Scholes open to new bid despite Hanson's Pounds 96m offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Scholes Group, the UK electrical equipment maker which last month agreed to
a Pounds 96.1m takeover bid from Hanson, the Anglo-US conglomerate,
yesterday took the unusual step of saying it was open to higher offers.
Mr Bill Riches, chairman, said: 'Clearly I want the best possible deal for
shareholders and if there are any other potential bidders out there it is
obviously in their interests for all the information to be presented.'
He denied he was directly soliciting a higher offer, but said the board had
recommended the Hanson bid only so it could present its own case to
shareholders, particularly regarding its relationship with ABB, the
Swedish-Swiss electrical giant, from which it licenses key technology.
Scholes revealed that ABB had warned that it would end the agreements if
Hanson's offer were not successful. ABB supports the Hanson bid and has
given an irrevocable undertaking to accept the offer in respect of its 4.3
per cent stake.
Originally Scholes wanted to buy Hanson's Crabtree business. But Mr Riches
said Scholes could not accept the conditions ABB had placed on its support
for a rights issue.
After ABB's warning, Scholes started discussions with Felten &amp; Guilleaume, a
German electricals group, to replace ABB's technology. Mr Riches said he was
confident that Scholes could reach an agreement if the Hanson offer were not
concluded. This 'would be in the best interests of Scholes'.
Although the Scholes board judged the offer 'fair', he said it had only
recommended the bid because a hostile offer document would have given 'an
unfair view of the company's situation'.
Scholes yesterday reported a 63 per cent jump in pre-tax profits to Pounds
7m for the year to June 30. Turnover was 5 per cent higher at Pounds 66m
with UK volumes slightly down.
It said in the absence of the Hanson offer, it would have recommended a 25
per cent increase in dividends reflecting 'confidence in Scholes' prospects
for the future'.
Hanson's offer of 250p a share in cash represents 20 times earnings, which
rose 60 per cent to 12.3p.
Lex, Page 14
News digest, Page 17
</TEXT>
