<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow steady ahead of inflation
data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices were mostly flat in listless trading yesterday as dealers
and investors remained on the sidelines awaiting a lead from the bond
market, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was just 1.95 firmer at
3,755.76, never having strayed far from its opening mark throughout the
session. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 edged up 0.04 to
457.93, while the American Stock Exchange composite finished 0.62 higher at
442.22 and the Nasdaq composite 2.14 ahead at 722.61. Trading volume on the
New York Stock Exchange came to 259m shares.
As on Monday, equities took their cue from bonds. The Treasury market was
subdued in early trading because participants were reluctant to commit funds
ahead of the afternoon auction of Dollars 17bn in new three-year notes. In
the event, the auction was deemed a modest disappointment, which led to
slight selling of bonds, but the general lack of action in the Treasury
market, where the yield on the 30-year bond edged ahead to 7.57 per cent,
ensured that stocks remained becalmed.
Equity investors were also wary of the market yesterday because of the
approaching release of July inflation figures. The producer and consumer
price indices are due to be published today and tomorrow, and analysts warn
that if the inflation numbers are worryingly high the Federal Reserve,
already troubled by recent strong growth in the labour market, could decide
to raise interest rates once more to cool down the economy.
Bank stocks were marginally weaker, unsettled by talk of higher interest
rates. Bankers Trust declined Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 67, Chase Manhattan
Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 35 3/4 and Chemical Bank Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 37
7/8 .
Other financials were also lower, with the securities houses Salomon down
Dollars  3/8 at Dollars 42 3/8 , Merrill Lynch off Dollars  3/4 at Dollars
35 7/8 , Bear Stearns Dollars  3/8 lighter at Dollars 16 3/8 and Morgan
Stanley Dollars  3/8 cheaper at Dollars 62 1/2 .
Leading technology issues were lifted by reports that a top mutual fund was
positive on the sector. Texas Instruments rose Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 80
1/4 , IBM added Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 64 1/2 and the Nasdaq-quoted Intel
appreciated Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 59 1/4 .
Shares in the Equitable insurance group fell Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 20 as
second-quarter earnings came in below market expectations, partly because of
a sharp drop in profits at the Equitable's securities unit, Donaldson Lufkin
&amp; Jenrette.
Storage Technology receded Dollars 2 to Dollars 37 and Network Systems,
quoted on the Nasdaq market, rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 9 1/8 after the
two companies announced plans to merge later this year in a stock-for-stock
transaction.
Colgate-Palmolive moved forward Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 53 1/4 after an
analyst at securities house Morgan Stanley raised her investment rating for
the stock from 'hold' to 'buy'.
</TEXT>
