<PROFILE>_AN-EHJD9AERFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940810
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 94 / International Company News: The Limited slides in second
quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Continuing weakness in sales of women's clothing caused net profits at The
Limited, the US retailing group, to tumble to Dollars 53.8m in the second
quarter to July from Dollars 68.2m in the same period last year, the company
said yesterday.
However, Nordstrom, another clothing retailer, showed a strong recovery.
The Limited saw good performances from its lingerie, men's, girls' and
personal care products businesses during the quarter, but these were
insufficient to outweigh poor results from the The Limited and Lerner New
York chains, where store-for-store sales fell by 13 per cent.
Group sales fell to Dollars 1.59bn from Dollars 1.69bn and earnings per
share to 15 cents from 19 cents. For the half-year, sales fell to Dollars
3.07bn from Dollars 3.21bn, net income to Dollars 101.1m from Dollars
112.5m, and earnings per share to 28 cents from 31 cents.
Among The Limited's best performers was the Bath &amp; Body Works personal care
products business, which recorded the highest store-for-store sales
increases in the company. The Limited expects to open its first Bath &amp; Body
Works stores in the UK this year in partnership with Next, the British
retailer.
Mr Leslie Wexner, chairman and chief executive, said stocks in the women's
apparel businesses were planned to avoid an overhang of summer merchandise
into the autumn. 'As a result, we are positioned to improve the sales and
earning opportunities as our fall merchandise moves into the stores,' he
said.
The Limited's fall was in sharp contrast with that of Nordstrom, which
lifted net income to Dollars 63m from Dollars 42.7m on turnover up 6 per
cent at Dollars 1.08bn. The company said the rise was mainly attributable to
better margins, particularly on women's clothing.
Earnings per share rose to 77 cents from 52 cents. For the half-year, net
income was 76 per cent ahead at Dollars 95m.
</TEXT>
