<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 94 / UK Company News: BPP advances 4% to Pounds 3.47m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in BPP Holdings rose 25p to 215p yesterday after the the education
and training group announced increased profits and an improvement in the
performance of Linguarama, its lossmaking language training subsidiary.
Pre-tax profits rose 4 per cent to Pounds 3.47m (Pounds 3.34m) in the first
half of 1994, helped by a strong performance from the professional training
division. Turnover edged ahead from Pounds 24m to Pounds 24.7m.
Linguarama, which plunged to a Pounds 728,000 loss last year, incurred an
interim deficit of Pounds 30,000 (Pounds 40,000). However, it has broken
even during the past three months, and management is optimistic of a profit
for the second half.
Linguarama suffered from the economic downturn in Europe, because it offers
language services to businesses and has a strong presence on the Continent,
particularly Germany.
The language business has been restructured, with closures in Japan and
Belgium, and although it has been forced to take on further price cuts,
business volumes are finally recovering.
The professional training division, which has focused recent expansion on
building up its BPP Law school and bank training business, saw profits
increase from Pounds 1.15m to Pounds 1.38m.
Publishing was affected by the loss of a sizeable accountancy training
client which has now turned competitor, and profits were down Pounds 127,000
at Pounds 1.27m.
Markus Verbeek, the Dutch business training subsidiary, has seen further
profits growth, but this will result in BPP having to pay about Pounds 5.5m
when it buys out the 32.3 per cent minority shareholders in April.
Academic education, which comprises the MPW sixth-form colleges, contributed
Pounds 684,000 (Pounds 584,000).
The most important time for the group's profits performance is during the
next few months - the start of the academic year - when it achieves the bulk
of sales for text books, distance learnings and A level courses.
However, management is confident that improved economic conditions will
result in further earnings recovery.
The company recommended an interim dividend of 3.1p (3p), which tracked a
0.1p increase in earnings per share to 7.7p.
</TEXT>
