<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 94 / Film success lifts PolyGram
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The low-budget movie Four Weddings and a Funeral helped PolyGram, the
London-based music and film group, lift half-year net income 14.7 per cent
to Fl 234m. (Pounds 85.5m).
PolyGram, which is 75 per cent owned by Philips of the Netherlands, said
that while music markets worldwide were healthy, its performance had been
held back by a paucity of new hits.
Mr Alain Levy, president, said the group would now begin making bigger
budget films and look for other companies to help share the costs.
Four Weddings and a Funeral, which topped the film charts in the US, the UK
and France, has so far grossed Dollars 125m (Pounds 81m). Mr Levy expected
final takings to be Dollars 150m-Dollars 200m. Only 35 per cent of the final
profits from the film were included in the first-half results.
Mr Levy said the first half had been PolyGram's most active period so far in
the film business, with seven new releases. Several of these had been
unsuccessful, however, including Backbeat, the story of the fifth Beatle.
He said revenues from films and non-music videos rose 56 per cent and now
represented 10.9 per cent of group sales.
While PolyGram's music sales had been hampered by a lack of new hits,
prospects for the second half were good, with albums expected from Stevie
Wonder, Boyz II Men, Amy Grant and Vanessa Williams.
Mr Levy said the classical music market had improved. Luciano Pavarotti's My
Heart's Delight had sold 400,000 copies. The singer extended his exclusive
worldwide contract with PolyGram into the next century.
PolyGram had failed to acquire rights to this year's football World Cup
concert featuring Pavarotti, Placido Domingo and Jose Carreras. These had
gone to Warner. The three tenors' recording of their World Cup concert in
1990 had been a best-seller for PolyGram.
Group net sales rose 14.1 per cent to Fl 3.6bn. Income from operations rose
6.6 per cent to Fl 340m. Earnings per share rose 8.3 per cent to Fl 1.30. Mr
Levy said the smaller increase in earnings was the result of last year's
issue of 10m new shares.
Lex, Page 16
