<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 94 / No coasting now the easy gains are over: How Barclays Bank
has rebounded so far and so fast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Martin Taylor, chief executive of a bank that has taken only 18 months to
switch from making a Pounds 242m loss to rivalling Lloyds as the most
profitable and best capitalised of the big UK banks, had little truck
yesterday with the suggestion that Barclays made too much money in the first
half.
Mr Taylor, who joined the board nine months ago to restore Barclays'
fortunes, pointed out that its average post-tax return on equity for the
past six years had been 4 per cent. 'That sort of return does not just
damage banks, it destroys them,' he said.
Barclays made an annualised return on equity of 23.6 per cent (21 per cent
excluding an Pounds 87m surplus from disposals) and its tier 1 ratio of
shareholders' funds to risk-weighted assets rose to 7 per cent. These were
in line with Lloyds' 21.9 per cent return, and 7.1 per cent tier 1 ratio.
Given Barclays' loss for 1992, and its decision to cut its dividend then,
its Pounds 1.04bn pre-tax profits for the first six months impressed
outsiders. 'We're starting to see the makings of a very great bank if they
stay on track,' said Mr Hugh Pye, banking analyst at Barclays' investment
bank BZW.
Yet a closer examination of the results does not suggest a bank coasting
towards ever higher returns. Operating profits fell by Pounds 108m to Pounds
1.23bn as it shrank loans and competed in an over-crowded UK market. All but
Pounds 23m of the Pounds 701m rise in pre-tax profits came from a fall in
bad debt charges.
The fall in bad debts was more pronounced than at other banks. Its Pounds
306m provision is only 0.29 per cent of loans and advances, compared with
0.80 per cent in the same period last year. This is only just more than half
Lloyds' figure of 0.55 per cent (excluding problem country provisions).
Although the ratio of total provisions to troubled and non-performing loans
rose from 31.8 to 35.9 per cent, the low level of new provisions could
indicate that Barclays either over-provided for bad loans during the worst
times, or is making inadequate provisions for fresh problems.
In practice, it is hard to calculate what a normal level of provisions
should be. Given continuing low inflation, bankers have started to guess at
long-term provisions figures of about 0.7 per cent for a full year. This is
not far from Barclays' half-year charge of just below half that.
Mr Taylor was unwilling to make predictions, pointing out that bad debt
charges in the last economic cycle rose to well above former peaks. 'It is
difficult to keep in mind how extremely high by historical standards
provisions have been. They really have been out of the window.'
Mr Pye argues that Barclays' swing in provisions may be more pronounced than
other banks' because it made large bad debt charges late in the last cycle.
'Their bad debts have been rather squashed up, so I don't think it is a sign
of imprudence that the charge is so low,' he said.
Even if provisions are appropriate, their low level means that Barclays will
have to improve operating performance in the next year to sustain rises in
profits. The UK clearing bank's 5 per cent operating improvement was largely
due to staff cuts, and income is under strong pressure.
Mr Taylor exhibited a mixture of caution and bullishness about the
prospects. On the one hand, he argued that it would be impossible to
maintain return on equity of above 20 per cent given the degree of
competition in retail banking. 'It is bound to be competed away to some
extent.'
On the other, he also emphasised the strength of operating businesses such
as Barclaycard. Their size would help them to design and sell products at
lower cost.
'We are starting to exercise that leadership. We're not sitting here waiting
for people to slice bits off us. They do that at their peril,' he said.
Mr Taylor said Barclays would continue to try to employ capital better,
cutting higher-risk assets and shifting capital towards those with a lower
risk-weighting and higher margins. Securitisation and other measures helped
reduce its risk-weighted assets by 7 per cent to Pounds 94.7bn.
Yet the easiest gains may be over in terms of reducing its poor assets,
while higher margins on those such as mortgages have already narrowed. This
will make it harder to find good uses for the bank's growing equity capital
 -up from Pounds 5.33bn to Pounds 5.9bn, with retained earnings of Pounds
530m.
This might not appear too pressing a worry given Barclays' return on equity
in the first half. Yet Mr Taylor emphasised that the bank has yet to prove
that it can make consistent returns. 'We are conscious that we owe our
shareholders a fair bit, and we are beginning to pay it back.'
If anything, that may make Mr Taylor's personal task harder. Having been in
place full-time only since the start of the year, he cannot claim much
credit for yesterday's results. By the time shareholders look to him to
demonstrate his worth, Barclays will be operating in a tougher world.
Lex, Page 16; Details, Page 18
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Barclays.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6021 National Commercial Banks.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>FIN  Interim results.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MKTS  Market shares.
