<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 94 / Observer: Ryrie rules
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
So the City of London has a soul after all - though it is perhaps something
of a pity that it takes a disaster of Rwandan proportions to stir it.
An extremely pukka collection of financiers have appended their names to the
City of London Emergency Rwanda Appeal (COLERA), launched yesterday and
chaired by Sir William Ryrie, former boss of the IFC, the private sector arm
of the World Bank.
The target is to pull in Pounds 1m over the next fortnight. 'City people are
not always what they seem,' says Ryrie, who has mostly found himself pushing
on an open door. Fully alive to the criticisms of aid donations not reaching
their targets, Ryrie has asked for progress reports from the charities
concerned which, he adds, will be a 'good discipline' for them, too.
Cheques, please, payable to COLERA (Rwanda)/DEC, and addressed to Disasters
Emergency Committee, 17 Grove Lane, London SE5 8RD.
